        <title>Listening to the long ringdown: A novel way to pinpoint the EOS in neutron-star cores</title>
            <categories>astro-ph.HE gr-qc hep-ph nucl-th</categories>
            <comments>4 pages, 2 figures, Quark Matter 2025 Proceedings</comments>
            <license>http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/</license>
            <abstract>Gravitational waves (GWs) from binary neutron star (BNS) merger remnants complement constraints from the inspiral phase, mass-radius measurements, and microscopic theory by providing information about the neutron-star equation of state (EOS) at extreme densities. We perform general-relativistic simulations of BNS mergers using EOS models that span the uncertain high-density regime. We find a robust correlation between the ratio of energy and angular momentum lost during the late-time post-merger GW signal - the long ringdown - and the EOS at the highest densities in neutron star cores. Applying this correlation to post-merger GW signals reduces EOS uncertainty at several times saturation density, where no direct constraints currently exist.</abstract>
